==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Margrave
<hw>Mar"grave</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G.
<ets>markgraf</ets>, prop., lord chief justice of the march;
<ets>mark</ets> bound, border, march + <ets>graf</ets> earl, count, lord
chief justice; cf. Goth. <ets>gagr⟦eum⟧fts</ets> decree: cf. D.
<ets>markgraaf</ets>, F. <ets>margrave</ets>. See <er>March</er> border,
and cf. <er>Landgrave</er>, <er>Graff</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Originally, a lord or keeper of the borders or marches in
Germany.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The English equivalent of the German title of
nobility, <xex>markgraf</xex>; a marquis.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margravine</ent>⟦br⟧
